# Restaurant Management System - Cursor AI Rules

## Project Context
This is a restaurant management system with AR/VR menu capabilities built with Next.js, TypeScript, and modern web technologies.

## Tech Stack Rules

### Framework & Language
- ALWAYS use Next.js 14+ with App Router
- ALWAYS use TypeScript with strict mode
- NEVER use JavaScript files
- ALWAYS use 'use client' or 'use server' directives appropriately

### Styling
- ALWAYS use Tailwind CSS for styling
- PREFER Shadcn/ui components over custom components
- NEVER use inline styles or CSS modules
- ALWAYS make designs mobile-first and responsive

### Database & ORM
- ALWAYS use Prisma ORM
- ALWAYS define proper TypeScript types from Prisma schema
- NEVER use raw SQL queries without Prisma
- ALWAYS handle database errors with try-catch

### State Management
- USE React hooks (useState, useEffect, useContext) for client state
- USE Server Components for data fetching when possible
- USE React Query/SWR for client-side data fetching with caching
- NEVER use Redux unless specifically requested

### Real-time Features
- ALWAYS use Socket.io for real-time updates
- IMPLEMENT proper connection/disconnection handling
- ALWAYS type Socket.io events with TypeScript

### AR/VR Components
- ALWAYS use @google/model-viewer for AR features
- USE Three.js only when model-viewer is insufficient
- OPTIMIZE 3D models (recommend GLB format)
- ALWAYS provide fallback for non-AR devices

## Code Style Rules

### File Naming
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- Utilities: camelCase (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- API routes: lowercase with hyphens (e.g., `get-orders.ts`)
- Types: PascalCase in `types` folder

### Component Structure
```typescript
// ALWAYS follow this structure
'use client'; // if client component

import statements...

// Types/Interfaces
interface Props {
  // ...
}

// Component
export default function ComponentName({ props }: Props) {
  // Hooks first
  // Event handlers
  // Render logic
  
  return (
    // JSX
  );
}
```

### API Route Structure
```typescript
// ALWAYS follow this structure
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';
import { prisma } from '@/lib/prisma';

export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  try {
    // Auth check
    // Business logic
    // Return response
    return NextResponse.json({ data });
  } catch (error) {
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: 'Error message' },
      { status: 500 }
    );
  }
}
```

### Error Handling
- ALWAYS use try-catch blocks in async functions
- ALWAYS return user-friendly error messages
- ALWAYS log errors to console in development
- NEVER expose sensitive error details to client

### Type Safety
- ALWAYS define TypeScript interfaces/types
- NEVER use 'any' type (use 'unknown' if necessary)
- ALWAYS use Zod for runtime validation
- ALWAYS type API responses

## Feature-Specific Rules

### Authentication
- USE NextAuth.js for all authentication
- IMPLEMENT role-based access control (RBAC)
- PROTECT all API routes with authentication middleware
- STORE sensitive data in environment variables only

### Real-time Orders
- EMIT Socket.io events for all order status changes
- UPDATE all connected clients (kitchen, waiter, customer)
- IMPLEMENT optimistic updates on client side
- HANDLE connection failures gracefully

### AR Menu
- LOAD 3D models lazily
- SHOW loading states for 3D models
- PROVIDE 2D fallback images
- OPTIMIZE for mobile performance

### Database Queries
- ALWAYS use Prisma's type-safe queries
- IMPLEMENT pagination for list queries
- USE database indexes for frequently queried fields
- AVOID N+1 query problems

### Form Handling
- USE React Hook Form for all forms
- VALIDATE with Zod schemas
- SHOW field-level error messages
- IMPLEMENT optimistic UI updates

## Performance Rules

- ALWAYS use Next.js Image component for images
- IMPLEMENT code splitting with dynamic imports
- USE React.memo for expensive components
- LAZY load AR/3D components
- IMPLEMENT proper caching strategies
- MINIMIZE bundle size

## Security Rules

- NEVER expose API keys in client code
- ALWAYS sanitize user inputs
- IMPLEMENT rate limiting on API routes
- USE HTTPS in production
- VALIDATE all data on server side
- IMPLEMENT CSRF protection

## Testing Rules (when generating tests)

- WRITE unit tests for utilities
- WRITE integration tests for API routes
- USE React Testing Library for component tests
- MOCK external dependencies
- AIM for >80% code coverage on critical paths

## Documentation Rules

- ADD JSDoc comments to complex functions
- DOCUMENT all API routes with expected input/output
- MAINTAIN README with setup instructions
- DOCUMENT environment variables

## Git Commit Message Format

When suggesting commits:
```
feat: Add AR menu viewer component
fix: Resolve order status update issue
refactor: Improve database query performance
docs: Update API documentation
```

